============================================================
 README - Clean Boot Service Manager (msconfig style)
============================================================

CREATOR: fahimnob

WHAT THESE FILES DO
------------------------------------------------------------
This mimics msconfig's:
  Services tab -> "Hide all Microsoft services" -> "Disable all"

There are 2 self-contained files (no PS1 dependencies):

1) Disable-NonMicrosoftServices.bat
   - Auto-elevates to Administrator (automatic, no manual UAC needed)
   - Backs up ALL current service settings to your Desktop
     (file named ServiceBackup_<date>_<time>.csv)
   - Then disables every service that is NOT signed by
     Microsoft (third-party services only). Microsoft
     services are left untouched, same as msconfig.
   - Everything is built into this single .bat file

2) Restore-Services.bat
   - Undoes the changes by restoring services back to the
     settings saved in the backup CSV.
   - Automatically finds the newest backup file on your
     Desktop, OR you can drag a specific backup CSV file
     on top of this .bat file to restore from that one.
   - Everything is built into this single .bat file


HOW TO USE
------------------------------------------------------------
STEP 1 - Disable non-Microsoft services
  1. Download both .bat files to the same folder
  2. Double-click "Disable-NonMicrosoftServices.bat"
  3. It will automatically request admin privileges (you
     will see a UAC prompt - click "Yes")
  4. Wait for it to finish - it will list every service it
     disabled, then pause so you can read the results
  5. Restart your computer (REQUIRED)

STEP 2 - Test / troubleshoot
  Use your PC normally and see if your issue is gone. This
  is the standard "clean boot" troubleshooting method.

STEP 3 - Undo / restore everything back to normal
  1. Double-click "Restore-Services.bat"
  2. It will automatically request admin privileges (you
     will see a UAC prompt - click "Yes")
  3. It will automatically find your latest backup on the
     Desktop and restore every service
  4. Restart your computer (REQUIRED)


IMPORTANT NOTES / WARNINGS
------------------------------------------------------------
- These scripts will automatically request Administrator
  privileges when double-clicked. No manual configuration
  needed.

- This DISABLES third-party services - this can include:
    * Antivirus software
    * Audio / graphics driver services
    * Backup software
    * Game launchers (Steam, Epic Games, etc.)
    * VPN software
    * Printing services
    * Network services
  This is expected and matches what msconfig's "Disable all"
  does. Do not leave these disabled permanently - this is a
  TEMPORARY troubleshooting step only.

- DO NOT delete the ServiceBackup_*.csv file on your Desktop
  until you have restored your services and confirmed
  everything works normally again.

- If you run Disable-NonMicrosoftServices.bat more than once,
  it will create a new backup file each time. Restore-Services
  always uses the NEWEST one unless you drag a specific file
  onto it.

- A restart is REQUIRED after running either script for
  changes to fully take effect.

- If services fail to restore, try:
  1. Run Restore-Services.bat again
  2. Restart manually via Start menu
  3. If still broken, use System Restore to revert to a
     previous restore point


TESTING SAFELY (RECOMMENDED)
------------------------------------------------------------
If you want to try this without any risk to your real PC:
  1. Turn on "Windows Sandbox" (Windows 10/11 Pro/Enterprise):
     Start menu -> search "Turn Windows features on or off"
     -> check "Windows Sandbox" -> restart
  2. Open Windows Sandbox
  3. Drag both .bat files into the Sandbox window
  4. Run them there - the Sandbox resets completely when
     closed, so nothing affects your real system.


TECHNICAL DETAILS
------------------------------------------------------------
- The scripts use PowerShell (included with Windows) to:
  * Query service information
  * Identify Microsoft vs third-party services (checks
    binary path for System32/SysWOW64/Windows)
  * Manage service startup types and status
  * Create CSV backups for safe restoration

- Microsoft services are detected by checking if their
  binary path includes Windows system directories. This
  ensures core OS functionality remains intact.

- All operations require Administrator privileges for
  security and safety.

- No external dependencies or separate files required.


TROUBLESHOOTING
------------------------------------------------------------

Q: Script says "PowerShell execution policy"?
A: The scripts bypass this automatically. If it still fails,
   try running as Administrator (right-click > Run as admin).

Q: Some services didn't get disabled?
A: Some services might be protected by Windows or require
   different methods to disable. The script uses safe,
   standard Windows APIs.

Q: I lost internet / audio / graphics?
A: Run Restore-Services.bat immediately. This is why the
   backup is important! Restart your PC after restoring.

Q: Where is my backup file?
A: Check your Desktop for a file named
   "ServiceBackup_YYYY-MM-DD_HH-MM.csv"

Q: Can I restore from an old backup?
A: Yes! Drag the specific CSV file onto Restore-Services.bat,
   or edit the command line and pass the path as an argument.

Q: What if I accidentally deleted the backup?
A: If you haven't restarted yet, run Restore-Services.bat
   and it will search for any ServiceBackup_*.csv files.
   If you've restarted, use System Restore to revert changes.


